            "answer_text": "I publish in both, and the strongest commonality is having to convince your target community that your work is both interesting and important. Both allow you to make your argument using whatever tools you like: rhetoric, simulation, analogy, mathematics, metaphor, experiment. But you also need to understand what kind of arguments your community finds compelling. Bringing in new kinds of arguments may require multiple publications just to establish them as a valid approach. Both require a deep understanding of the existing literature, and your argument should demonstrate that you have that understanding, usually by citing (appropriately) existing work. ",
